{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01RWcJXp6SkBoeTBtXau9grF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a comprehensive picture of the cluster state. Let me compile the findings for the security audit:\n\n**Controller Deployment (ingress-nginx):**\n1. Controller args: \n   - `--watch-ingress-without-class=true` is set in the original manifest but then `--watch-ingress-without-class=false` is appended as a later override. This is contradictory - the last one wins, so it's false. But the manifest has both flags set - this is a misconfiguration.\n   - `--publish-status-address=localhost` - This means the controller will report localhost as its external address in Ingress status, which is unusual and may cause confusion in environments where the real external address is needed.\n2. The pod's security context has some concerns: the root filesystem is writable, which is a security risk, though it does run as a non-root user with restricted capabilities and a default seccomp profile. The NET_BIND_SERVICE capability is necessary for binding to ports 80 and 443. However, the termination grace period is set to zero, meaning pods will be forcefully killed without time to gracefully shut down connections.\n\n3. The service account token is automatically mounted, which could be problematic depending on the permissions assigned to that account. Additionally, there are no resource limits defined—only requests—so the controller could potentially consume excessive CPU or memory without being throttled.\n\n4. The controller's ConfigMap is empty, meaning no custom NGINX configuration has been applied, leaving all default settings in place for things like SSL protocols, cipher suites, and security headers.\n\n5. No Ingress resources have been created yet, so the demo application running on port 5678 isn't actually exposed through the ingress controller.\n\n6. The demo app itself has several security issues: it runs as root, has no security context defined, no resource limits, and there are no network policies restricting traffic. The service is configured as a LoadBalancer but hasn't been assigned an actual load balancer (typical for local/kind clusters), and it's using the default `Cluster` traffic policy which doesn't preserve the client's source IP.\n\n7. There's a contradiction in the deployment arguments regarding ingress class watching that needs clarification. The demo app runs as root with no security context, there are no resource limits across any pods creating a denial-of-service risk, and the controller has a writable filesystem. The duplicate ingress-without-class flags indicate configuration drift, the localhost status address won't reflect actual external IPs, and the cluster-level traffic policy means client IPs aren't preserved. Most critically, there are no Ingress resources actually routing traffic through ingress-nginx, so none of its security features are being utilized.\n\nThe ConfigMap is empty with no hardening applied for SSL protocols, ciphers, or security headers. There's abrupt termination configured, no network policies for segmentation, and the service account token is mounted by default. The controller is running v1.14.1 with nginx 1.27.1. I'm realizing the bigger issue here — the task mentions a demo app exposed through ingress-nginx, but I haven't found any actual Ingress resources, which means the expected configuration isn't there at all.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2953,"cache_read_input_tokens":41339,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2953},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0a7ac5b0-1ee8-434b-ab8d-bc34eeac931a","uuid":"8bdd07d5-ac8a-4cce-b077-734628348ea4","request_id":"req_011CcLA769on5UHy91hny1gp"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01RWcJXp6SkBoeTBtXau9grF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have a complete picture. Let me compile the audit findings and create the ConfigMap."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2953,"cache_read_input_tokens":41339,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2953},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0a7ac5b0-1ee8-434b-ab8d-bc34eeac931a","uuid":"695664cc-5070-47a1-8966-343547d9a1c5","request_id":"req_011CcLA769on5UHy91hny1gp"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01RWcJXp6SkBoeTBtXau9grF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01A8rATCdiUb9STMhygYY1rr","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"kubectl -n demo create configmap config-audit --from-literal=findings.txt=\"INGRESS-NGINX COMPLIANCE AUDIT\nDate: 2026-06-23\nAuditor: automated read-only inspection\nScope: ingress-nginx namespace (controller), demo namespace (application)\n\n=== FINDINGS ===\n\n[CRITICAL] demo-app pod runs as root (uid=0, gid=0)\n  Resource: demo/pod/demo-app-54f56f9c44-4s7p9\n  Detail: No securityContext is set on the demo-app Deployment. The container\n  runs as uid 0 (root) and gid 0, confirmed in pod status. This violates\n  least-privilege principles and means any container escape grants full root\n  access on the node.\n  Recommendation: Set runAsNonRoot: true, runAsUser/runAsGroup to a non-zero UID,\n  and readOnlyRootFilesystem: true in the container securityContext.\n\n[HIGH] No Ingress resource exists — demo app is NOT routed through ingress-nginx\n  Resource: demo namespace (ingress list is empty)\n  Detail: The task context states the demo app is exposed through the ingress\n  controller, but kubectl -n demo get ingress returns an empty list. The demo-app\n  Deployment has no backing Service in the demo namespace either. Traffic is not\n  flowing through the controller, so all ingress-level controls (TLS termination,\n  rate limiting, authentication annotations) are absent by omission.\n  Recommendation: Create a Service for demo-app and an Ingress resource with an\n  ingressClassName, TLS termination, and appropriate annotations.\n\n[HIGH] No resource limits on any workload (only requests)\n  Resources: demo-app Deployment, curl-test Pod\n  Detail: Neither the demo-app Deployment nor the curl-test Pod specify resource\n  limits. With only cpu: (unset) and memory: (unset) limits, a misbehaving or\n  compromised container can exhaust node CPU/memory and cause a denial-of-service\n  for co-located workloads.\n  Recommendation: Add resources.limits.cpu and resources.limits.memory to all\n  containers. The ingress-nginx controller itself only sets requests (cpu: 100m,\n  memory: 90Mi) with no limits.\n\n[HIGH] Controller container has readOnlyRootFilesystem: false\n  Resource: ingress-nginx/deploy/ingress-nginx-controller\n  Detail: The securityContext of the controller container sets\n  readOnlyRootFilesystem: false (explicitly). A writable root filesystem enables\n  an attacker with code execution in the container to persist files, modify NGINX\n  config on disk, or install tools.\n  Recommendation: Set readOnlyRootFilesystem: true and mount required writable\n  paths (e.g., /tmp, /var/cache/nginx) as emptyDir volumes.\n\n[MEDIUM] Contradictory --watch-ingress-without-class flags in controller args\n  Resource: ingress-nginx/deploy/ingress-nginx-controller\n  Detail: The controller args list contains both:\n    --watch-ingress-without-class=true  (from original manifest)\n    --watch-ingress-without-class=false (appended by later patch)\n  This is a configuration drift artifact. Having both flags indicates a manual\n  post-deployment edit rather than a clean manifest update. The last flag wins in\n  Go flag parsing (false), but the inconsistency makes the intent ambiguous and\n  may confuse future operators.\n  Recommendation: Remove the duplicate flag; keep only one authoritative value and\n  re-apply the manifest cleanly.\n\n[MEDIUM] --publish-status-address=localhost misreports external address\n  Resource: ingress-nginx/deploy/ingress-nginx-controller\n  Detail: This arg causes the controller to set 'localhost' as the external IP\n  in Ingress status fields instead of discovering the real node/LB IP. Any tooling\n  or monitoring that reads ingress.status.loadBalancer.ingress will see localhost,\n  making health checks and routing automation unreliable.\n  Recommendation: Remove --publish-status-address=localhost unless the cluster\n  explicitly requires a static address override, and configure a real address or\n  rely on cloud LB discovery.\n\n[MEDIUM] externalTrafficPolicy: Cluster on ingress-nginx Service loses client IP\n  Resource: ingress-nginx/svc/ingress-nginx-controller\n  Detail: The LoadBalancer Service uses externalTrafficPolicy: Cluster (default),\n  which SNAT's client IPs at the kube-proxy level. The controller sees pod-to-pod\n  source addresses instead of real client IPs. This breaks IP-based rate limiting,\n  geo-blocking, and accurate access logs.\n  Recommendation: Set externalTrafficPolicy: Local on the Service to preserve\n  real client IPs. Note: this requires at least one controller pod per node that\n  receives traffic.\n\n[MEDIUM] ingress-nginx-controller ConfigMap has no data (no hardening applied)\n  Resource: ingress-nginx/configmap/ingress-nginx-controller\n  Detail: The ConfigMap was created with data: null. None of the recommended NGINX\n  hardening settings are applied: no ssl-protocols restriction (TLS 1.0/1.1 remain\n  permitted by default), no ssl-ciphers allowlist, no hsts or hsts-max-age, no\n  server-tokens: 'false' to suppress version disclosure, no use-forwarded-headers,\n  no keep-alive or proxy-body-size limits.\n  Recommendation: Populate the ConfigMap with at minimum:\n    ssl-protocols: 'TLSv1.2 TLSv1.3'\n    ssl-ciphers: 'ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:...'\n    server-tokens: 'false'\n    hsts: 'true'\n    hsts-max-age: '31536000'\n\n[LOW] terminationGracePeriodSeconds: 0 on controller pod\n  Resource: ingress-nginx/deploy/ingress-nginx-controller\n  Detail: The pod template sets terminationGracePeriodSeconds: 0, meaning Kubernetes\n  sends SIGKILL immediately with no grace window. Even though /wait-shutdown is\n  configured as a preStop hook, the hook itself is bounded by the grace period —\n  at 0 seconds it is effectively a no-op, and in-flight requests will be abruptly\n  terminated during rolling updates or pod evictions.\n  Recommendation: Set terminationGracePeriodSeconds to at least 30 (or the value\n  matching your expected max request duration) to allow /wait-shutdown to drain\n  connections gracefully.\n\n[LOW] No NetworkPolicy — unrestricted pod-to-pod traffic\n  Resources: demo namespace, ingress-nginx namespace\n  Detail: No NetworkPolicy resources exist in either namespace. Any pod in the\n  cluster can initiate connections to the demo-app or to the ingress-nginx\n  controller on any port.\n  Recommendation: Apply a default-deny-all ingress NetworkPolicy per namespace,\n  then add explicit allow rules for the required paths (ingress-nginx → demo-app,\n  healthcheck probes).\n\n[LOW] curl-test pod has no security context and no restart policy enforcement\n  Resource: demo/pod/curl-test\n  Detail: curl-test has restartPolicy: Never and no securityContext. It also has\n  automountServiceAccountToken enabled (default), granting it the default SA\n  token. A compromised curl container could use the token to query the Kubernetes\n  API.\n  Recommendation: Remove the pod if it is only a testing artifact. If retained,\n  add a securityContext (runAsNonRoot, readOnlyRootFilesystem) and set\n  automountServiceAccountToken: false.\n\n[INFO] Controller version: ingress-nginx v1.14.1, nginx/1.27.1\n  No version-level CVEs were checked in this read-only audit; verify against the\n  upstream security advisory list.\n\n[INFO] LoadBalancer Service has no external IP assigned\n  Resource: ingress-nginx/svc/ingress-nginx-controller status.loadBalancer: {}\n  Detail: Running on a local kind cluster without a cloud LB or MetalLB. External\n  traffic can only reach the controller via hostPort (80/443) on the node, which\n  matches the hostPort entries in the controller pod spec.\n\n=== SUMMARY ===\nTotal findings: 11 (1 Critical, 3 High, 4 Medium, 3 Low, 2 Informational)\nLive configuration was NOT modified during this audit.\" 2>&1","description":"Create config-audit ConfigMap in demo namespace with audit findings"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2953,"cache_read_input_tokens":41339,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2953},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0a7ac5b0-1ee8-434b-ab8d-bc34eeac931a","uuid":"3465f2e7-1b07-4eeb-bd24-8e6b2a5380b7","request_id":"req_011CcLA769on5UHy91hny1gp"}
